Peer Assessment II

1 Background

As a statistical consultant working for a real estate investment firm, your task is to develop a model to predict the selling price of a given home in Ames, Iowa. Your employer hopes to use this information to help assess whether the asking price of a house is higher or lower than the true value of the house. If the home is undervalued, it may be a good investment for the firm.

2 Training Data and relevant packages

In order to better assess the quality of the model you will produce, the data have been randomly divided into three separate pieces: a training data set, a testing data set, and a validation data set. For now we will load the training data set, the others will be loaded and used later.

load("ames_train.Rdata")

Use the code block below to load any necessary packages

library(statsr)
library(dplyr)
library(BAS)
library(MASS)
library(ggplot2)

2.1 Part 1 - Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

When you first get your data, its very tempting to immediately begin fitting models and assessing how they perform. However, before you begin modeling, its absolutely essential to explore the structure of the data and the relationships between the variables in the data set.

Do a detailed EDA of the ames_train data set, to learn about the structure of the data and the relationships between the variables in the data set (refer to Introduction to Probability and Data, Week 2, for a reminder about EDA if needed). Your EDA should involve creating and reviewing many plots/graphs and considering the patterns and relationships you see.

After you have explored completely, submit the three graphs/plots that you found most informative during your EDA process, and briefly explain what you learned from each (why you found each informative).

2.1.1 Prices in Different Neighborhood

The mantra in real estate is Location, Location, Location! But how much prices could vary among neighborhoods?

ggplot(data = ames_train, aes(x = Neighborhood, y = price)) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    ggtitle("Prices in Diffeerent Neighborhood") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 20, hjust = 0.5),
          axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

From the boxplot above, we can see the properties in NridgHt and StoneBr tend to have highest prices with large vairiance, Meanwhile, those in BrDale and MeadowV are always much cheaper.

2.1.2 The Area of the Property and Its Price

Typically, we think larger house will have higher price. Now we have enough data points to examine the assumption.

ggplot(data = ames_train, aes(x = area, y = price)) +
    geom_point() +
    ggtitle("Property Area v.s. Price") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 20, hjust = 0.5),
          axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

From this plot, we can see there is a general positicve trend between area and price. Meanwhile, when the house is very large, the variance of the house price also grows greatly. There are also some abvious outliers, with large area but very low price. Besides, the house has highest price is not the house has largest area.

2.1.3 Property Age v.s. Price

Is older property more expensive or the opposite? We have pros for both arguments: One the one hand, new property has better maintenaince condition, thus should be more expensive; On the other hand, older property could have higher historical value and tends to be located in better geographical areas, contributing to its price. Lets make a scatter plot to examine the arguments.

ggplot(data = ames_train, aes(x = 2017-Year.Built, y = price)) +
    geom_point() +
    ggtitle("Property Age v.s. Price") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 20, hjust = 0.5),
          axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
    xlab("Property Age")

Overall, the older the property, the lower the price. Those properties that have highest price are those built recently new. There arent much difference of prices among the properties with age larger than 50 years. However, its worth to notice that there are fewer houses with higher age.

2.2 Part 2 - Development and assessment of an initial model, following a semi-guided process of analysis

2.2.1 Section 2.1 An Initial Model

In building a model, it is often useful to start by creating a simple, intuitive initial model based on the results of the exploratory data analysis. (Note: The goal at this stage is not to identify the best possible model but rather to choose a reasonable and understandable starting point. Later you will expand and revise this model to create your final model.

Based on your EDA, select at most 10 predictor variables from ames_train and create a linear model for price (or a transformed version of price) using those variables. Provide the R code and the summary output table for your model, a brief justification for the variables you have chosen, and a brief discussion of the model results in context (focused on the variables that appear to be important predictors and how they relate to sales price).

To start with, I built the prediction model with variables area, MS.Zoning, Neighborhood, Condition.1, Bldg.Type, Overall.Qual, Year.Built, Bsmt.Qual, Full.Bath. I selected these variables because they all seem have a strong relationship with the price.

par(mfrow = c(2,2))

boxplot(price ~ Full.Bath, data = ames_train,
        xlab = "Full.Bath", ylab = "Price")

hist(ames_train$price)

2.2.3 AIC Model Selection Method

Firstly, lets use the AIC(Aikake information criterion) stepwise selection procedure. This is a typical frequentist model selection method. This procedure is a backward method, which starts from the full model and tries to remove one variable at a time, aiming to minimize AIC.

2.2.6 Summary

These three model selection methods give me totally different results for model selection. This is because the first two are frequentist mothod with different penalty criteria, while the thrid one is a Bayesian method. More specifically, AIC tries to select the model that most adequately describes an unknown, high dimensional reality. This means that reality is never in the set of candidate models that are being considered. On the contrary, BIC tries to find the TRUE model among the set of candidates.

In the next part, I will use the model with BIC model selection method, since it is less prone to overfitting.

2.2.9 Section 2.5 Overfitting

The process of building a model generally involves starting with an initial model (as you have done above), identifying its shortcomings, and adapting the model accordingly. This process may be repeated several times until the model fits the data reasonably well. However, the model may do well on training data but perform poorly out-of-sample (meaning, on a dataset other than the original training data) because the model is overly-tuned to specifically fit the training data. This is called overfitting. To determine whether overfitting is occurring on a model, compare the performance of a model on both in-sample and out-of-sample data sets. To look at performance of your initial model on out-of-sample data, you will use the data set ames_test.

load("ames_test.Rdata")

Use your model from above to generate predictions for the housing prices in the test data set. Are the predictions significantly more accurate (compared to the actual sales prices) for the training data than the test data? Why or why not? Briefly explain how you determined that (what steps or processes did you use)?

prediction_test = exp(predict(m_bic, ames_test))
sqrt(mean((prediction_test - ames_test$price)^2, na.rm = TRUE))
## [1] 25905.65

To compare the performance of the model on training set and testing set, I calculated the RMSE for the testing set. This time, the RMSE is 25905.65, which is much lower than that for the training set. This fact indicates that our model has good generalization ability.

Note to the learner: If in real-life practice this out-of-sample analysis shows evidence that the training data fits your model a lot better than the test data, it is probably a good idea to go back and revise the model (usually by simplifying the model) to reduce this overfitting. For simplicity, we do not ask you to do this on the assignment, however.

2.3.3 Section 3.3 Variable Interaction

Did you decide to include any variable interactions? Why or why not? Explain in a few sentences.

I included two pairs of variable interaction: area:Full.Bath. From the following simple linear regression, we can see that area, Full.Bath and area:Full.Bath all appear siginificant, and the negative sign of the coefficient of area:Full.Bath indicates that althrough in general, the larger the area, the more the bathrooms, the higher price, with all the others held constant, increase of number of bathrooms will have a negative influence on the effect of area to price.

2.3.5 AIC Model Selection Method

prediction_inv = data.frame(predict(m_bic_final, ames_validation, level = 0.95, interval = "prediction"))
# number of predictive confidence intervals that contains the true price
true_count = nrow(ames_validation[log(ames_validation$price) >= prediction_inv$lwr | log(ames_validation$price) <= prediction_inv$upr,]) - sum(is.na(prediction_inv))
# percentage
true_count / nrow(ames_validation)
## [1] 0.9055118

Over 90% of the 95% predictive confidence intervals contain the true price of the house in the validation data set.

From this result, I think my final model properly reflects uncertainty.

2.5 Part 5 Conclusion

Provide a brief summary of your results, and a brief discussion of what you have learned about the data and your model.

From the data and my model, I learned that the price of a house could be predicted given its area, zoning category, building type, overall quality, year built, year remodeled, exterior quality, basement quality and the number of full bathrooms.

From the coefficients of the model, we can know that the larger the area, the higher the overall quality and basement quality, the newer the house is built or remodeled, the higher the price tends to be. Besides, with all the else held constant, a house locating in Residential Low Density zoning or of the building type 2FmCon tends to has the highest prices. One counter-intuition result is that the coefficient of the number of full bathrooms is negative. This could be due to its collinearity with other variables such as area.
